title: For Sale:  **reduced** Nagant M1895 cal. 7.62x38 7 shot revolver + 100 rds of ammo
postcontent:
Russian Nagant M1895 (7.62x38) 7 shot revolver.  Includes holster. 

I also have another 100 rds of 7.62x38 ammo for sale

From a website... "Definitely an interesting handgun from an era gone by, the 7-shot Nagant Revolver is an extremely unique design dating back to the 1890s. The most interesting design point is that upon cocking the hammer, the cylinder pushes forward in an attempt to seal off escaping gas; the cartridge case itself then provides the final seal at the point of firing and supposedly adds 50 to 150 fps to the bullet's initial velocity. 

Designed by the Nagant Brothers (Emile and Leon) of Liege, Belgium, the original design was accepted by the Russians in 1895. The initial shipments were produced at Liege, Belgium and exported to Russia. Around 1898, the Russians then initiated their own production at their Tula Arsenal. Originally designated to be replaced as frontline issue after the adoption of the TT30 in 1930, the production on these military weapons actually continued up through 1945 and they could still be found in the hands of reservist troops and police into the 1950s."

 Norwegian Gevaer M/1894 Krag-Jorgesen long rifle in 6.5x55mm, Kongsberg arsenal date 1902. Very early date, produced just prior to the Norwegian succession from Sweden in 1905. One of over a thousand Antique and Modern Collectible firearms, including Military, Sporting, Custom and Tactical guns, as well as Edged Weapons and Militaria we have for sale at Jackson Armory (see our other listings), this is a a very RARE prize for the Smith & Wesson Collector! This is a Smith & Wesson “Pre-27” .357 Magnum DA Revolver. A 5-Screw Smith, these guns (with the high-frame screw) were only made between 1950-1957. Adding rarity to the pistol, it has a factory nickel finish and a pair of gorgeous aged ivory grips with gold-plated S&W medallions. Also, the pistol has the rare, and sought-after 3 ½” barrel. As was standard on these pistols, it has an adjustable rear sight, a ramp front sight (with a dollop of red paint on the ramp), a finely-checkered top strap, and grooved front and rear grip straps. The ivory grips (worth about $1000. In their own right!) fit this gun like a glove! To say that the pistol is handsome is an understatement! The pistol has faint turn marks on the cylinder, and the painted sight ramp, and that’s it – NO cosmetic issues whatsoever, the bore is absolutely MINT, trigger pull is very smooth, overall, the pistol easily rates 95%+ condition.

349 Cash
